name: Cultural Point of Interest, North Korea Uncovered
description:
http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/korea/index.php?contents+2218+2008-06+77+2

This Google Earth project offers an extensive mapping of North Korea's economic, cultural, political, and military infrastructures. Through the topic menu, users of this program have easy access to geographical information on North Korea's agriculture projects, aviation facilities, communications, hospitals, hotels, energy infrastructure, financial services, leisure destinations, manufacturing facilities, markets, mines, religious locations, restaurants, schools, and transportation infrastructure. In addition to locations of economic interest, this map also displays anti-aircraft locations, the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) and Northern Line Limit Line (NLL), incarceration facilities, political monuments, political residencies, military bases, and nuclear facilities.

properties.name: Anak Tomb No. 1
properties.description: The site includes several groups and individual tombs - totalling about 30 individual graves - from the later period of the Koguryo Kingdom, one of the strongest kingdoms in northeast China and half of the Korean peninsula between the 3rd century BC and 7th century AD. The tombs, many with beautiful wall paintings, are almost the only remains of this culture. Only about 90 out of more than 10,000 Koguryo tombs discovered in China and Korea so far, have wall paintings. Almost half of these tombs are located on this site and they are thought to have been made for the burial of kings, members of the royal family and the aristocracy. These paintings offer a unique testimony to daily life of this period. Location: 38Â°29'2" N, 125Â°32'34" E Go to the Anak Tomb No. 1 - Complex of Koguryo Tombs on the UNESCO site. Search Wikipedia for Anak Tomb No. 1 - Complex of Koguryo Tombs. Search Google for Anak Tomb No. 1.[Check for Updates]

properties.name: Botanical Garden, Pleasure Grounds, and Zoo
Building for animals gifted to Kim Jong il
properties.description:
http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/korea/index.php?contents+1381+2006-05+51+18

There is a house of gift animals presented to the leader Kim Jong Il by Jonas Wahlstrom, director of the Skansen Aquarium in Sweden, at the Central Zoo at the foot of the scenic Mt. Taesong. Opened in October Juche 74 (1985), it is composed of an aquarium, a reptile section, a mini-ape section and a night animal section. 

It houses very rare animals. There live diverse animals of some 80 kinds such as pygmy marmoset, the smallest species of apes in the world which gives all kinds of sweet gestures even on manâs finger, mouthbrooder the female of which lays spawns and the male fertilizes them and then the female keeps them in its mouth until they are incubated and night ape with extraordinarily large eyes which usually sleeps in the daytime and acts only at night. 

The tenders have spruced up the living environment of the animals and look after them with utmost care in conformity with their ecological characteristics. The animals have completely adapted themselves to the environment and their breeding coefficient grows with the passage of time by dint of their efforts. 

Lots of people come to the house of gift animals and enjoy a rest there.

properties.name: Burial Mounds (Alleged victims of US bombing: 400 mothers 102 children)
properties.description:
http://www1.korea-np.co.jp/pk/090th_issue/99041401.htm
Sinchon Museum: 

Located in the northern part of  South Hwanghae Province, the Sinchon Museum serves as a reminder of mass genocide of Koreans by the U.S. army during the 1950-53 Korean War.

In this tiny city of Sinchon alone, as many as 35,380 people, roughly a quarter of its total population, were killed by U.S. soldiers.

Mothers and children were separately shoved into manmade caves by the U.S. soldiers, who poured gasoline upon them, set fire and locked the entrance.

Crying in their caves with no-way-out, hundreds of thousands of mothers and children were wiped out in this cruel manner.

It contains 40 bowling alleys, electronic amusement facilities, a restaurant, a shop and saunas. 

It is always full of working people and students who visit here in their spare time, to say nothing of holidays and red-letter days. 

The alley hosts the DPRK bowling championships every year. Bowlers from the Pyongyang Bowling Alley Sports Club show fine results in the championships. 

Foreigners also visit this place. 

Its employees take good care of bowling equipment and service facilities and are always kind to visitors.

Jongbangsan Pleasure Ground
properties.description:
http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/korea/index.php?contents+2317+2008-09+80+11

South Hwanghae Province boasts of Mt. Jangsu called âHwanghae Kumgangâ. 

The name of Mt. Jangsu was derived from the fact that many long-lived people have come forth in and around it since olden times. It has been widely known as a tourist destination for it presents enchanting scenery. 

The most beautiful landscape in the mountain is a valley with twelve bends which is believed to be made by the mysterious trick of a legendary dragon. The valley is surrounded by cliffs and thick with trees, lending an entrancing scene to every bend. It is home to many scenic spots including the Hyon Hermitage, a unique building among old Korean structures, Jara (terrapin) Rock, Toksuri (eagle) Rock, Saja (lion) Rock and Jangsu (longevity) Falls. 

Pojok Peak (745 m), the highest in the mountain, overlooks the scenery of Mt. Jangsu, Lakes Unpha and Jangsu, cooperative fields and peaks in Mts. Kuwol and Suyang, the tourist attractions in the west coast. 

In the mountain are the relics and remains of the Fort on Mt. Jangsu which Koguryo erected while building sub-capital South Pyongyang there in the mid-4th century, the folds of Mt. Jangsu and natural monuments including Forsythia ovata of Mt. Jangsu. 

The mountain was built as a tourist destination. It draws people all the year round. This year the climbing path to the twelve bends was extended to the shore of Lake Unpha via Pojok Peak and the fort by looped and sightseeing roads. 

Mt. Jangsu will be more beautiful in the era of Songun.

properties.name: Junggang Revolutionary Site
properties.description:
Pyongyang, July 9 (KCNA) -- Junggang in the northern tip of Korea is on the bank of the River Amnok. 
    The name is derived from the fact that the area is located in the middle part of the river. It is associated with the undying feats performed by Kim Hyong Jik, an indomitable revolutionary fighter and an outstanding leader of the anti-Japanese national liberation movement in Korea. 
    He was engaged in energetic revolutionary activities in Junggang from December Juche 7 (1918) to the next autumn. 
    President Kim Il Sung came to the place, following his father Kim Hyong Jik and helped him in his revolutionary activities, receiving a patriotic and revolutionary education from him. 
    Kim Hyong Jik stayed in the Junggang Inn with his family and was a doctor by occupation. He waged an energetic struggle to unite proletarians under the banner of anti-Japanese struggle and the separate armed groups. 
    He organized the Junggang Branch of the Korean National Association and made the most of the Junggang Post Office to contact with revolutionary organizations at home and abroad to rally firmly the broad anti-Japanese patriotic forces around the association. 
    He gave tasks to revolutionaries at Junggang Sinsong School, Tonggu Church, Tonggu Chemist's Shop and mixed himself with young men and women to educate them in the consciousness of national independence and advanced ideas and lead them to the anti-Japanese patriotic struggle. 
    The Junggang Revolutionary Site has been built as a centre of the revolutionary education. 
    The revolutionary site has been visited by more than two million working people, youth and students over the last years.

properties.name: Konnyu Islet Pleasure Park
properties.description:
http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/todaykorea/index.php?contents+3809+2008-10+114+25

http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/korea/index.php?contents+1811+2007-08+67+22

A ship-shaped Konyu Islet on the Taedong River can be viewed from the top of Mangyong Hill in the capital city of Pyongyang. 

The islet is associated with the exploits of President Kim Il Sungâs great-grandfather Kim Ung U in the battle for sinking the US imperialist aggressorsâ ship General Sherman and the immortal history of grandfather Kim Po Hyon who fought resolutely against the Japanese imperialists. 

Recently this historic islet has been turned into a fine pleasure park for people. 

After a visit to the Mangyongdae Revolutionary Site working people cross a floating bridge linking Mangyongdae to the islet to have a good time. 

A wood overgrown with apricot, poplar, pink acacia and other trees, a well-paved driveway covered with fragrant flowers, lawns, paths through the wood, 2,000-seat outdoor tables and chairsâ¦ Everything on the islet arouses quiet feeling. 

The pleasure park has facilities for sports and folk games such as basketball, volleyball, mini-football and ssirum (Korean wrestling). A performance can be given on an open-air stage equipped with sound facilities on a flat lawn. 

People can angle for carp and crucian carp in a man-made pond filled with water of the Taedong River and cook them to eat. 

Everybody likes to take a speedboat that goes round the islet, adding much to the beauty of the landscape. 

The pleasure park is always visited by many people.

properties.name: Kwangbop Temple
properties.description:
http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/korea/index.php?contents+1510+2006-10+56+22

The Kwangbop Temple in Taesong-dong, Taesong District, Pyongyang, is a temple built in the period of the Koguryo Dynasty (277 BCâAD 668). A large number of temples were built in Pyongyang in the reigning period of King Kwanggaetho. The Kwangbop Temple is one of them. 

It was repaired in 1727 and reconstructed to its original state in Juche 79 (1990) after it was completely destroyed by the bombing of the US imperialists in July 1952 during the Fatherland Liberation War. 

The temple is composed of the Haethal Gate, the Chonwang Gate, the Taeung Hall, the east and west Buddhist monasteries and an octagonal five-storeyed pagoda. Its buildings are located symmetrically with the pagoda as the centre. 

It was a common method of building temples in the period of Koguryo to locate buildings on three sides centring on a pagoda. 

The Taehung Hall, the main building of the temple, is a grandiose two-storeyed building with a hip-saddle roof. It has three kan on the front and three kan at the side on a magnificent platform laid with well-trimmed stones, and has red round pillars with cattle tongue-shaped ornamental supports on them. It has been decorated in glossy gold paint. 

There are carved images of young monks on elephants and lions in the Haethal Gate and those of four heavenly kings in the Chonwang Gate. 

Preserved in the temple are a lotus pond handed down from antiquity and the monument to the Kwangbop Temple erected in 1727 and the monument to the extension and painting of the Kwangbop Temple. The epitaph on the monument to the Kwangbop Temple records a legend about nine dragons and 99 ponds of Mt. Kuryong of Taesong. 

The temple is a valuable cultural legacy showing the developed architecture of the people in Koguryo and constitutes a priceless relic in the research of the history and culture of Koguryo and other states at that time.

properties.name: Lake Samji
properties.description:
Lake Samji was formed as a result of the lava flow, which blocked the river, when a volcanic eruption took place a million years ago. The lake is 4.5 kilometers in circumstance, and 3 meters deep. A grand monument, lodges and a hall lie on the shores of the lake.

Lake Samji is a place where Kim Il Sung took a rest and imbued warm feelings of patriotism into his men on the way of advance into the Musan area in May Juche 28 (1939). Under the guidance of Kim Jong Il, a grand monument was built at this picturesque place in May Juche 68 (1979).

properties.name: Lake Yonpung
properties.description: Lake Yonpung is a reservoir for irrigation situated between Anju City and Kaechon County, South Pyongan Province. It is 14.87 square kilometres wide and 89.3 kilometres round. This lake is of great importance as a source of the Pyongnam Irrigation System and its scenery is very lovely. The limpid lake abounds in fishes. There is an episode that a foreigner who enjoyed a rest on Lake Yonpung was so fascinated with its beauty that he was oblivious of his next day's schedule. There are many rest homes and camps.

properties.name: Mangyongdae Children's Union Camp
properties.description:
http://www.tongilkorea.net/?action=fullnews&showcomments=1&id=3692

Mt. Ryongak in the suburbs of Pyongyang is over 290 metres high. Its peak looks like a dragon ready to fly up with its mouth opened. Hence its name Mt. Ryongak (Dragon Mountain). 

It is otherwise called "Mt. Kumgang in Pyongyang" because of its beautiful scenery. More than 600 varieties of plants occur on the mountain including Clerodendron trichotomum Thunb, zelkova, pipsissewa and Amitostigma gracile Schlecther. 

The historical relics such as the Pobun hermitage and the Ryonggok private school show the simple yet refined architecture of our ancestors in the Koryo Dynasty. The Mangyongdae Children's Union Camp is situated in a scenic spot. 

In recent years the mountain has been refurbished by the policy of the Workers' Party of Korea to ensure the people more bountiful and cultured lives. 

A sightseeing path, a road and a park where working people can enjoy pleasant break have been newly built. 

An artificial pond and the "Dragon's Palace" in the park enrich the beautiful scenery of the mountain. Various types of stone tables and 1,200 chairs resembling varied shapes such as leaves and roots have been placed there. 

Now the mountain serves as a resort for the working people and foreigners. 

Pictures:
http://www.flickr.com/photos/kernbeisser/sets/72157601886662998/

properties.name: Manwoldae
properties.description:
The place where the royal palace of Koryo was located. Only ruins of the foundation of the big palace still exist. It was built in 919. It was burnt in the invasion of the Red Kerchieved Rebel Army in 1361.

http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/todaykorea/index.php?contents+3118+2007-11+103+26
Manwoldae, Koryoâs Palace Site 

There is a site of the royal palace at the southern foot of Mt. Songak in Kaesong City, Korea. It is called Manwoldae. 
It was the main royal palace for about 500 years in the period of Koryo (918-1392), the first unified state in the Korean history. It occupied an area of 1,250,000mÂ². Manwoldae was originated from âMangwoldaeâ, the site for moon-viewing in the palace on lunar January 15. 

Mangwoldae was changed into Manwoldae with the passage of time. 

Koryo completed in 919 the construction of Manwoldae, gorgeous and magnificent. 

The royal palace is divided into the district of royal halls and residences and the national government district with important offices. The royal district alone covered nearly 390,000mÂ². 

Manwoldae is characterized by an architectural group of buildings constructed on highly-laid foundations, revealing the roofs of the buildings in magnificent tiers. 

The front gate to the national government district was the Kwanghwa Gate in the east. Inside the Kwanghwa Gate and some way straight forward to the west before turning to the north, there was the Sungphyong Gate, the entrance to the royal district. And inside it was the Tongnak Pavilion. Between the Sungphyong Gate and the Sinbong Gate in the north was a large yard called Kujong, a venue of kyokgu which is similar to the present polo. 

Straight ahead of the Kujong was the two-storeyed Sinbong Gate, the second gate to the royal area and the largest and the most magnificent one inside the palace. 

Koryo kings and government officials frequently ascended the gatehouse to see the kyokgu games in Kujong or inspect the army. 

Passing through the Sinbong Gate would lead to the Changhap Gate on a higher topographical position; and stepping into it, one can see a small yard, before which stands an elevated foundation with four stone stairs of imposing sight. 

This is the very foundation on which was built the Hoegyong Hall and the other main part of the architectural group of buildings of Manwoldae. 

The 33-step stone stairs are so precipitous that they look very high. On top of the stairs was the gate to the Hoegyong Hall, the grandest of the palace buildings. 

There were several large building sites behind the Hoegyong Hall site. However, US troops who occupied the southern half of Korea after August 15, 1945, bulldozed them for the construction of their quarters. 

To the west of the central architectural group high up on the foundation were the royal houses, where the kings worked and lived usually. Many sites are still visible there. 

Beautiful gardens and arbours were to be seen on the hill north of the royal part. 

Manwoldae, the site of the royal palace of Koryo, is one of the valuable cultural heritages, which shows the architecture and peopleâs talents in the period of Koryo succeeding to Koguryo.

properties.name: Meari Shooting Ground
properties.description:
http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/korea/index.php?contents+1505+2006-10+56+17

The Meari Shooting Ground, which people frequent, is in Chongchun Street in Pyongyang. Residents of the capital city and overseas compatriots and foreign guests on a visit to Korea enjoy their rest here. 

It was commissioned in February Juche 85 (1996). It has an area of 12,000 square metres and consists of the main hall, an auxiliary building and an outdoor shooting range. 

The main hall is composed of the first and second floors and there is an indoor shooting range on the second floor. 

The indoor shooting range has pistol and rifle shooting places. 

The pistol shooting distance is 25 metres and the rifle shooting distance 50 metres. As the shooting places are equipped with electronic sensors, shooters can find out the results in their places. So they give favourable impressions on the shooters. The indoor shooting range has 120 spectatorsâ seats. 

The outdoor shooting range has 15 shooting places. Shooters aim at animal targets with pistols and rifles. The animal targets are live pheasants. 

The shooting ground is furnished with an e-game room, an interview room, a dining room, a soft drink counter and an open-air grilling site. 

Director Pyon Tong Sop said, âThe number of visitors to our shooting ground increases with every passing day. Weâll improve service and install more convenient facilities to enable them enjoy the break.â

properties.name: Mt. Kuwol National Park
properties.description:
Biosphere Reserve Information
http://www.unesco.org/mabdb/br/brdir/directory/biores.asp?code=DRK+02&mode=all

The Mount Kuwol Biosphere Reserve, situated on the west coast of the Democratic Peopleâs Republic of Korea and 100 kilometres south-east of Pyongyang, consists of a 954 meter-high mountain, adjacent coastal wetlands, lagoons and river estuaries, and agricultural areas. Both the core area and the buffer zone are part of the Mount Kuwol Nature Reserve, which was designated in 1976. The main objective of the core area is to protect the old typical forest ecosystem of Korea, which survived the damages of the Korea War. The presence of both pristine and rehabilitated forests makes Mount Kuwol an important area to study the ecological changes and effects of forest rehabilitation as well as the associated biodiversity. Ginseng (Panax ginseng), Forsythia ovata and other native plants are protected here. The only human activities in the core area are sightseeing and visits to the Woljong Temple, an old historic relic. There are limited human activities in the buffer zone, and the transition area, which includes forests, plain areas, wetlands and many rivers, is where most economic activities take place. The wetland, which includes the coastal Unryul Migratory Birds Reserve, play an important conservation role as habitats for shore birds and critical areas for many migratory bird species of north-east Asia such as black-faced spoonbill (Platalea minor), Chinese egret (Egretta eulophotes) and red-crowned crane (Grus japonensis).

The Biosphere Reserve constitutes one of the most important rice production areas of DPR Korea. The conservation of essential ecological and hydrological functions of the Mount Kuwol ecosystems is important for the maintenance of sustainable rice production and related aquaculture and fishery. The foot of Mount Kuwol is rich in medicinal herbs, which are widely used for Koryo medicine, the traditional medicine of Korea. 

Some 70,000 people live in the Biosphere Reserve, which is also an area of recreation and attracts more than 500,000 tourists annually, mainly due to its close distance from Pyongyang. Mount Kuwol is an area of cultural importance in Korea. There are many cultural and historical relics such as fortresses, temples, historical houses and tombs, related to the early development of Korea as well as to the origins of Buddhism, a heritage of importance to conserve.The management plan of the Biosphere Reserve will be incorporated in the general blueprint for land construction under the State Plan. Environmental protection aims mainly at afforestation of the transition area and the prevention of soil erosion.

properties.description:
http://www.tongilkorea.net/?action=fullnews&showcomments=1&id=3692
http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/korea/index.php?contents+1458+2006-08+54+14

Mt. Ryongak in the suburbs of Pyongyang is over 290 metres high. Its peak looks like a dragon ready to fly up with its mouth opened. Hence its name Mt. Ryongak (Dragon Mountain). 

It is otherwise called "Mt. Kumgang in Pyongyang" because of its beautiful scenery. More than 600 varieties of plants occur on the mountain including Clerodendron trichotomum Thunb, zelkova, pipsissewa and Amitostigma gracile Schlecther. 

The historical relics such as the Pobun hermitage and the Ryonggok private school show the simple yet refined architecture of our ancestors in the Koryo Dynasty. The Mangyongdae Children's Union Camp is situated in a scenic spot. 

In recent years the mountain has been refurbished by the policy of the Workers' Party of Korea to ensure the people more bountiful and cultured lives. 

A sightseeing path, a road and a park where working people can enjoy pleasant break have been newly built. 

An artificial pond and the "Dragon's Palace" in the park enrich the beautiful scenery of the mountain. Various types of stone tables and 1,200 chairs resembling varied shapes such as leaves and roots have been placed there. 

Now the mountain serves as a resort for the working people and foreigners.

Nam Gate
properties.description:
This is a renovation--propping up the original which sustained damage in the Korean War.

The South Gate was built between 1391 and 1393, at the same time as the inner citadel of the walled city. The citadel used to have seven gates, but only Nam Gate is left. During the Korea War is was severely damaged and rebuilt in 1954. 
On the gate there is a pavilion. Inside is Yonbok Bell. It was cast in 1346, is 3,3 meters high and weighs 14 tuns. The bell originates from Yonbok Temple, which was destroyed by fire in 1563. Until the beginning of the 20th century the bell was used to call the hours and this could be heard until 4 km from the city.

properties.name: P'yongyang Bell
properties.description:
KCNA

The Pyongyang Bell is one of the national cultural heritage of Korea. It has been preserved well in the colorfully painted bell-house north of the Taedong Gate on the bank of the Taedong River flowing through Pyongyang thanks to the national cultural inheritance preservation policy of the Workers' Party and the government of Korea. It was not certain when the original bell was cast. 
    The original bell was hanging in Pukjang Pavilion (northern commanding post) of the walled city of Pyongyang. The present one larger than the original one was cast in 1726 after its breakage owing to fire of the pavilion. 
    The bell is 3.1 meters high, 1.6 meters in diameter of its mouth and 0.3 meters thick. It weighs 13.513 tons. 
    Carved on the bell are images of Buddha, patterns of cloud, words, etc. Its hook depicts two twisted dragon heads (blue and yellow ones). The bell, one of the big bells in the period of the Ri Dynasty (1392-1910), has been called "famous thing of Pyongyang" for the gracefulness of its shape and beautiful peal ringing far and wide. 
    By the 1890s, the bell was stroke to open and close all the gates of the walled city at 4 in the morning and 22 in the evening and to inform the invasion by foreign troops, natural calamities, New Year's Day, auspicious and other events. The Japanese imperialists who illegally occupied Korea in the early 20th century banned the Korean people from approaching it, to say nothing of striking it, saying that the bell was the symbol of the Korean nation and its sound was permeated with the nation's soul. 
    President Kim Il Sung, who liberated the country in August Juche 34 (1945), saw to it to toll the bell on the eve of the New Year's Day that year to bring greater joy of national resurrection to the people.

properties.name: Phipa Resort
properties.description:
Pipha Island
The bathing resort extends to the south in front of Pipha Island which is 13 km east of Rajin and 6 km southeast of Sonbong The white sandy beach is glistening in gleaming sunlight and gin-clear water which makes the island an excellent resort. Lying long from east to west, the island appears to be a peninsula adjacent to the inland. But it is connected with a beach and pier. Pipha, a musical instrument had given the island its name. Either it is called Phipa (an island preventing waves) or Korae (a whale on the sea). The Pipha Hotel is behind the island.

properties.name: Phophyong Revolutionary Site
properties.description:
Pyongyang, July 9 (KCNA) -- Lots of working people from all walks of life, youth and students in the DPRK are visiting the Phophyong Revolutionary Site on the birth anniversary of Kim Hyong Jik, an indomitable revolutionary fighter and an outstanding leader of the anti-Japanese national liberation movement in Korea (July 10. 1894). 
    It is situated in Kim Hyong Jik-township, Kim Hyong Jik County, Ryanggang Province. 
    He made an energetic revolutionary activity, crossing the Amnok River between the Phophyong area and Badaogou of China frequently from Juche 10 (1921) to Juche 13 (1924). 
    The Phophyong area was in a geographically favorable position for linking the northeastern area of China where many fighters for independence were concentrated with various parts of the homeland at that time. 
    There are many historical relics associated with the revolutionary activities of Kim Hyong Jik in the Phophyong Revolutionary Site including a church, a house of a person from Hamgyong Province, a noodle shop, a postal consignment agency and a house of an assistant to military police. 
    In the Phophyong Church he used to meet revolutionaries active in the homeland, converse with believers and teach revolutionary and patriotic songs to young people in particular. 
    Along with Kim Hyong Jik, Kang Pan Sok, an indomitable revolutionary fighter and an outstanding leader of the Korean women's movement, taught Korean language and propagated advanced ideas to women in the evening school set up at the house of the person from Hamgyong Province. 
    He sent instructions and materials needed for disseminating advanced ideas to domestic revolutionary organizations through the postal consignment agency. The noodle shop and the house of an assistant to military police serving the Phophyong MP Detachment were his secret liaison places for activities in the homeland. 
    He used the house close to the Dragon Rock as secret liaison place and a depot of weapons to be sent to armed groups and met operatives and advocates active in the homeland on Jonmo Peak behind the house. 
    There is the Phophyong Police Substation of Japanese imperialists where he was detained in the middle of December 1924. 
    There are in Kim Hyong Jik County the places where he escaped from the detainment and crossed the Amnok River.

properties.name: Pochonbo Revolutionary Site
properties.description:
http://www.kcckp.net/en/tourism/attraction/attract-view.php?2+4
http://www.kcckp.net/en/book/new_window.php?10+10003+5+8+english


Pyongyang, June 3 (KCNA) -- An increasing number of people are visiting the Pochonbo Revolutionary Battle Site with the approach of the 66th anniversary of the victory in the Pochonbo battle. A surprise attack on Pochonbo in Ryanggang Province was made on June 4, Juche 26 (1937) under the command of President Kim Il Sung. 
    The historic battle gave a telling blow to the colonial rule of the Japanese imperialists, who were making desperate efforts to stamp out the national spirit of the Korean people. It also inspired the Korean people with the belief that Korea was not dead but alive and they could certainly win victory if they fought against the Japanese imperialists. 
    In the Pochonbo battle site there are the Kusi barrage battle site, Konjang hill, the command post of the Pochonbo battle, a police substation, fire station, sub-county office, forest conservancy office, post office, agricultural experimental station, etc. 
    The Kusi barrage is located about 8 kilometers northwest of Pochonbo. The main unit of the Korean People's Revolutionary Army used a raft bridge in the barrage to cross the River Amnok. 
    Konjang hill is the place where the main unit, led by the president, made preparations for the battle, taking a daytime rest on the way to Pochonbo. On the hill the president issued a detailed battle order and, after the battle, conducted a political work among people while taking a rest. 
    The monument of dedicated poem "May Konjang Hill Shine Forever" was erected on the hill on the occasion of the 40th anniversary of the victorious battle. 
    At the command post there is a Korean poplar now preserved in glass tube. Near the tree the president commanded the battle. 
    There is also a machine gun which was posted for defending the headquarters during the battle. 
    The police substation, fire station, sub-county office, forest conservancy office and other attacked offices which were serving the Japanese imperialists are still kept in their original state. 
    The Korean people erected the president's statue in Pochonbo on June 4, 1955 to convey his exploits to posterity. 
    They also built a monument to his revolutionary activities and the Pochonbo revolutionary museum there. 
    The Pochonbo Revolutionary Battle Site is one of the centers for the education in the revolutionary traditions.

properties.name: Pothong Gate
properties.description: Pothong Gate is at the Pothong Riverbank, at the western end of Mansudae Street and the beginning of Chollima Street. In the 6th century, during Koguryo, this was the west gate of the central fort of Pyongyang. The gate was rebuilt in 1473. During the Korea War it was destroyed and later rebuilt. The gate has a stone base and on top of that a two-story pavilion.

Royal Villa
properties.description:
http://www.flickr.com/photos/kernbeisser/sets/72157605289608490/

This is the place where Yi SÅnggye, founder of the Yi dynasty and its first monarch (as King T'aejo), spent his last years after his abdication in 1402. After his death, the villa was converted into a shrine where ancestral rites were held. In the main hall, ancestral tablets for King T'aejo, his first and his second wife, and four generations of his ancestors are kept.

The original buildings from the late fifteenth century were burnt down by the Japanese in the late 16th century. The present buildings were reconstructed in 1610.

After T'aejo's abdication, his son sent emissaries to improve relations with his father. The disgruntled old man killed some of them and mistreated others. Hence the proverbial "Hamhung messenger" (í¨í¥ì°¨ì¬) for somebody who does not return in time.

properties.name: Rungnado Pleasure Park
properties.description:
http://www.tongilkorea.net/?action=fullnews&showcomments=1&id=3434

The Rungna Islet is situated on the River Taedong flowing through the central part of Pyongyang. 

The islet is nearly 1.3 square kilometres in area. 

Visible to the west of the islet is Moran Hill, a place of natural beauty rising high along the Taedong riverside, and to the east of the islet is Munsu Street which is lined on both sides with high-rise apartment buildings. 

The islet has now been converted into a recreation ground which is frequently visited by many people as their favourite haunt. The islet is walled in by well-trimmed granite so that land is not washed away by the river water. 

What attracts attention first on the islet is the May Day Stadium with 150,000 seats. 

In this stadium the opening and closing functions of the 13th World Festival of Youth and Students were held in Juche 78 (1989). "Arirang", a Kim Il Sung Prize laureate, was given successfully in Juche 91 (2002) and in Juche 94 (2005), calling forth a great response of the world. 

In addition, there are four open-air auxiliary stadiums of the May Day Stadium which are built up in such a way as to ensure smooth competition and training as well as a swimming pool and a boating ground. 

Seen on the islet are a wild cherry and a fir tree planted personally by President Kim Il Sung in April Juche 54 (1965). The state designated them as natural monuments and is specially protecting and taking care of them. 

On the islet there is a large flower garden and more than 40 flower beds. They are distributed rationally in keeping with lots of ground and beautiful flowers come into bloom in and out of season. 

Besides, peach-tree, sweet cherry trees, cherry trees and many other fruit trees are growing and pine-nut trees, fir trees, willows, gingko trees, etc. have formed forests. 

Arbours and pavilions convenient for the relaxation are set up exquisitely and animals for enjoyment, such as deer, parrots and monkeys are giving joy to the working people who enjoy their pleasant time, while having a rest, going round the small zoo which covers a space of 1,500 square metres. 

The islet is furnished with open-air facilities for holding sports, such as tennis, volleyball and basketball and for playing folk games and enjoying a variety of recreation. 

Added to these modernly-furnished restaurants and soft-drink stands on the islet afford convenience to the working people who visit the recreation ground. 

On the islet there are the Chongryu and Rungna bridges which were constructed for the improvement of traffic conditions of the citizens of the capital city of Pyongyang who visit there. 

Today, too, many people visit the islet to spend their pleasant time.

properties.name: Ryonggang Great Tomb
properties.description: The site includes several groups and individual tombs - totalling about 30 individual graves - from the later period of the Koguryo Kingdom, one of the strongest kingdoms in northeast China and half of the Korean peninsula between the 3rd century BC and 7th century AD. The tombs, many with beautiful wall paintings, are almost the only remains of this culture. Only about 90 out of more than 10,000 Koguryo tombs discovered in China and Korea so far, have wall paintings. Almost half of these tombs are located on this site and they are thought to have been made for the burial of kings, members of the royal family and the aristocracy. These paintings offer a unique testimony to daily life of this period. Location: 38Â°51'46" N, 125Â°24'54" E Go to the Ryonggang Great Tomb - Complex of Koguryo Tombs on the UNESCO site. Search Wikipedia for Ryonggang Great Tomb - Complex of Koguryo Tombs. Search Google for Ryonggang Great Tomb.[Check for Updates]

properties.name: Ryongmun Caves (Kujang)
properties.description:
http://www.kcckp.net/en/periodic/korea/index.php?contents+2393+2008-12+83+20

http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1426/

Caves in Kujang area are the underground karstic grottoes formed during the Quaternary of the Cenozoic Era in the limestone formations. Though their formation periods and lithological characters are same, they are different from one another in the size and scope according to the process of karstic evolution, as well as in the esthetical features according to the conditions of stalagmites and stalactites.



Ryongmun Cavern begins at the height of 370 meters above sea level and there are two main caves and some 20 branches so far developed. It is an underground cave 7 kilometers long, 40 meters high (at the highest place) and 3~ 4 meters wide in average, which has various forms of gorgeous stalagmites and stalactites bearing mysteriousness.and beauty.



Paekryong Cavern begins at the height of 470 meters above sea level, and some 5 kilometers of passageway has been currently exploited. Inside the cave various forms of animal figures, stone falls and columns exhibit breathtaking scenery, exciting manly feeling by its fascinating yet brisk appearance. Kaechon Flower Cave spreads out a "sea of flowers" by the stone flowers formed in the limestone formation, mostly containing mineral ores. The cave is characterized by its soft, beautiful and gorgeous appearance. Songam Cave consists of one main passageway and several branches with mysterious figures of stalagmites and stone flowers.

properties.name: Sakju Recreation Center
properties.description:
Pyongyang, July 1 (KCNA) -- There are many recreation centres in the DPRK. One of them is the Sakju Recreation Center. 
    It was built at the foot of Onjong Hill eight kilometers southwest of Sakju county, North Phyongan Province, in July Juche 66 (1977). 
    The center with a plottage of at least 23,000 square meters boasts three two-storied buildings of a unique style, a hot spring bathroom, sports and recreation facilities and all other conditions necessary for the rest of working people. 
    The center is surrounded by mountains and a stream is flowing in front of it. 
    It is open from April to October and from December to February next year. 
    Vacationing period is 15 days. 
    More than a hundred working people are now vacationing in the centre, while touring the Chongsudong Revolutionary Site, boating on lake Suphung, playing sports games and mountaineering.

properties.name: Samjiyon Grand Monument
properties.description:
Samjiyon Grand Monument

The statue of President Kim Il Sung stands on the centre. The torch tower and Revolutionary Monument stand on one side of the statue. They are 250 m wide.

A sculptural group 'Trumpeter of Advance' stands on the other side. And the 80 groups of sculptures stand in front against the Paektu Mountains and Lake Samji including the groups titled 'Motherland', 'Reverence', 'Advance', 'Camping' and 'Water of Motherland'.

The statue of the great leader Comrade Kim IL Sung is 15 m high and pedestal 4.5 m high. The torch tower is 50 m high (the body: 39 m high, the torch: 11 m high) and sculptural group 'Trum peter of Advance' 12 m high and other groups 6 m high on the average.

The sculptural group 'Trumpeter of Advance' won the People's Prize out of its high ideological and artistic character on the occasion of the 40th birthday of the DPRK.

Site of North Korea's first Cricket Game, April 2008
properties.description:
http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2008/04/25/77/0401000000AEN20080425002900315F.HTML
N. Korea to host first cricket tournament 

   LONDON, April 25 (Yonhap) -- North Korea will host its first cricket tournament with foreign players attending next week, a London-based newspaper said Thursday.

   The Twenty20 tournament will be held at an amusement park in Pyongyang with three visiting teams largely composed of expatriates from England, Australia, South Africa and Holland who are based in Shanghai, the Telegraph said.

   The North Korean team will be assisted by staff from the Indian and Pakistani embassies in Pyongyang, it added.

   "The tournament was planned by Bryan Clark, a British employee of the logistics firm DHL, which has an office in Pyongyang, and the Shanghai Cricket Club, which has been leading attempts to develop the game in China," the report said.

   It quoted a club member as saying that North Korea seemed like a challenge.

   "We were running out of new venues to play," the member Ainsley Mann, who runs Coca-Cola's bottling operations in China, was quoted as saying.

   Taesongsan Park, the venue of the games, was the only place in Pyongyang with a suitable expanse of grass, the daily said.

properties.name: Sonjuk Bridge
properties.description:
http://tkdtutor.com/10Patterns/Pattern%20Sets/ChanghonPatternSet/11PoEun/PoEunInfo.htm

Jong Mong Ju held the highest civil post in Koryo. Ri Song Gye, the first King of the Ri Dynasty, tried to win him over to his side, but Jong refused to betray Koryo. After Ri Song Gye was injured after falling from his horse during hunting, Jong tried to have him killed but failed. Later Ri Song Gye invited Jong to his house trying to convince him again to betray his lord. But Jong answered with a poem:

"Even if, I may die, die a hundred times,
Even if my skeleton may become dust and dirt,
And whether my spirit may be there or not,
My single-hearted loyalty to the lord will not change."

Then Ri Song Gye realized he could not convince Jong. On the night of April 4, 1392, he sent an assassin to Sonjuk Bridge who brutally killed Jong Mong Ju with an iron hammer. This well-known scholar advocated loyalty to the Koryo Dynasty against the usurpers. Sonjuk Bridge is located about 1 km east of Nam Gate, being situated at the south foot of Mt. Janam, which rises on the city centre. The small stone bridge dates from 1216. Later a bamboo grew up besides the bridge and from that the bridge got his name. In 1780 the bridge was closed for all traffic and since then it is a monument.

After having got rid of Jong Mong Ju, Ri Song Gye succeeded in usurping the throne in July 1392. The stone bridge has enjoyed the attention through generations. This became a historical bridge which hastened the replacement of the Koryo Dynasty by the Ri Dynasty. At first it was called Sonji but it was renamed as Sonjuk after his death remembering his "loyalty". The red marks on the bridge seem to be his blood.

The large park at the entrance of Abomey is the âPlace Goho.â Here you have the statue of King Behanzin, who fought against the French to defend Dahomey. This statue erected at the entrance of Abomey is a tribute to his efforts to protect the kingdom. This is the meeting place between the King and General Behanzin Dobbs in 1894. This is also the venue of the proclamation of Marxism Leninism on 30 November 1974 by the revolutionary military government of Benin. The place houses since the statue of King Behanzin.

http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-3451883/Commemorating-the-chief-the-politics.html

The giant statue was made in North Korea. it was inaugurated on April 9, 1979, in Abomey with an anti-imperialist speech given by Kerekou. The text at the foot of the statue, placed mainly for local pride, reads "Je n'accepterai jamais de signer aucun traite susceptible d'aliener l'independance de la terre de mes aieux."

Translation: "I will never agree to sign any treaty susceptible to compromise the independence of the land of my ancestors."

properties.name: Statue of Laurent Kabila
properties.description:
Picture:
http://www.esquire.com/cm/esquire/images/congo-monument.jpg

http://www.inthesetimes.com/article/3500/in_search_of_lumumba/
In a traffic circle near Kinshasaâs central bank stands a three-story high statue of the late President Laurent Kabila, who was a former ally of Lumumba and a Marxist guerrilla. Kabila fought against Mobutu for two decades. During the â80s, he disappeared into Uganda, turning into a diamond smuggler. In 1997, Kabila was back, installed as president by invading Rwandan and Ugandan troops, to fill the vacuum after Mobutu died of cancer.

From the neck down, the Kabila monument looks strangely like Kim Jong Il: baggy uniform, creased pants, the raised arm, a little book in his left hand. From the neck up, the statue is the thick, grim bald mug of Laurent Kabila (his son Joseph is the current president). âThe body was made in North Korea,â explains my driver Felix. In other words, the body is Kim Jong Ilâs, but with a fat, scowling Kabila head simply welded on.

properties.name: Statue of Samora Machel
properties.description:
http://www.samizdata.net/blog/archives/african_affairs/

 Near the botanic gardens is to be found a statue of Samora Machel, the first post-independence president of Mozambique. As it happens, this statue was given to Mozambique by the North Koreans and Kim Il Sung, which perhaps explains the slightly wacky style. However, the statue hasn't received much maintenance, and many of the words on the plaque below it have crumbled away. In particular, the whole section explaining when and how the statue was erected is gone, and there appears to have been no attempt to repair the sign and return Mr Kim's credit.

Suyang Mountain Fort Walls
properties.description: Near Changdae Peak during Koryo (936-1392) a mountain fort was built. The 8 km long walls connected the peaks. The walls are 6-7 meters high and 7-8 wide at the base and 3-4 meters wide at the top. Near Nam (South) Gate the walls are 14 meters wide. There are 14 bigger and smaller watchtowers.

properties.name: Suyangsan Waterfall
properties.description:
The Suyangsan Falls is situated at the foot of Mt. Suyang in Hakhyon-dong, Haeju City, South Hwanghae Province. 

It, 128 meters high and 12.5 meters wide, has been known as one of the eight scenic spots in the city from olden times. Now it produces a spectacular landscape, welded with the autumn tints of the surrounding areas. 

The two-stage falls has its headspring in the Jol Valley of Mt. Jangdae on the mountain range stretching southeastward from Mt. Suyang. 

The water which falls from the cliff, raising beads of water and spray, is reverberating in the valley. 

Spectacular are the landscapes of the autumn tints, spring flowers, summer verdure and winter snow around the falls.

properties.name: Taesongsan golf course
properties.description:
The Official Guide to Pyongyang G.C.
(Korean Central News Agency - Pyongyang, August 20, 2002)

The Pyongyang golf links is abustle with Pyongyangites, overseas Koreans and foreigners in this tourist season.
One can reach the golf links by covering just 27kms along the youth hero motorway from southeast of the Mangyongdae Schoolchildren's Palace.
Its plottage is over 120 hectares and the green covers 45 hectares, with a total length of the golf courses extending about 7km.
A course has 18 holes.
Among the courses are eight short-distance and long-distance courses and 10 middle-distance courses. They are diverse and peculiar in styles.
Traps of the links were created by use of high and low slopes at the foot of Mt. Sokchon. They are in full line with international standards.
There are golf clubs and balls and other apparatuses for more than 100 golfers to play at the same time. There is a modern club house with a floor space of over 2,700 square meters.
The house with a hip-saddle roof is supported by pillars which look like golf clubs. It gives all kinds of services to visitors. There are stalls inside the golf links.
The golf links boast a nearby thick woodland, diversity of plants and scenic beauty presented by lake Thaesong.
During breaks golfers enjoy collecting plants, boating and angling in the picturesque recreation ground.
Societies welcome.

properties.name: Thongounjong Pleasure Ground
properties.description: The Thonggun Pavilion is about 1 km north of the Uiju Nam Gate on the top of the mountain. The pleasure ground extends around the pavilion. On the north the River Amnok flows to the west and China is viewed over the river. The pleasure ground includes the Thonggun Pavilion, a tuckshop, the Monument to Chungminnimgong, a hexagonal pavilion, 7-storey quadrangular pagoda and Rakwon Pavilion.

properties.name: Tokhung-ri Tomb
properties.description: The site includes several groups and individual tombs - totalling about 30 individual graves - from the later period of the Koguryo Kingdom, one of the strongest kingdoms in northeast China and half of the Korean peninsula between the 3rd century BC and 7th century AD. The tombs, many with beautiful wall paintings, are almost the only remains of this culture. Only about 90 out of more than 10,000 Koguryo tombs discovered in China and Korea so far, have wall paintings. Almost half of these tombs are located on this site and they are thought to have been made for the burial of kings, members of the royal family and the aristocracy. These paintings offer a unique testimony to daily life of this period. Location: 38Â°57'39" N, 125Â°26'49" E Go to the Tokhung-ri Tomb - Complex of Koguryo Tombs on the UNESCO site. properties.name: Uiju Nam Gate
properties.description:
Lying in the heart of the city seat, it is 200 m of the Yangsil School. It was first built in 1617 and called Raehun Pavilion. After rebuilding in 1769, it was called "The Best House of Haedong" from 1795.
The Uiju Nam Gate played the role as an important gateway to the northern defense from the Koryo Dynasties (918-1392) to the Ri Dynasties (1392-1910). It is associated with the struggles of the righteous people, who withdrew the foreign invaders.
